            <!-- Overview -->
            <h2>Project Overview</h2>
            <p>
                I have always loved FFF 3D printing since I first learned about it. Making complex 3 dimensional shapes with just basic CAD
                skills and a machine that costs well under $1000? What isn't to love? Backed up by an incredible open source community,
                software, and endless material options, it is an absolutely incredible resource.
            </p>
            <p>
                While I love the extensive existing 3D printer options (and they have improved greatly since I started this project) I 
                they still leave me wanting more. The consumer 3D printer market is only now starting to get printers with chamber 
                temperatures acceptable for printing basic materials like ABS and Nylon, and no one even seems to be trying to get to 
                true engineering materials other than industrial printers. Additionally, the anisotropy of poor layer adhesion could be 
                mitigated by non planer or 5 axis printing.
            </p>
            <p>
                The plan I arrived at was to build a fully custom printer, making a bomb proof motion system out of metal allowing for 
                true engineering materials should I choose to use a compatible extrusion system. I also decided to use 3 independent 
                ball screw driven Z axes, creating 2 axis bed tilt capability for my dreams of attempting 5 axis FFF printing. While I
                Was at it, I decided I might as well make it big. Big printers are fun and if I get 5 axis going that will greatly
                benefit from a larger platform.
            </p>

