            <!-- Problem Statement -->
            <h2>Problem Statement</h2>
            <p>
                As I started this project, I quickly racked up a list of requirements and desired features.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Requirements:</li>
                <li>All core motion system components capable of operating at > 100C</li>
                <li>Bomb proof motion system allowing for future crazy projects</li>
                <li>Upgrade potential for 5 axis printing (2 axis bed tilt)</li>
            </ul>
             <ul>
                <li>Desired Features:</li>
                <li>Large format > 300mm in all axes</li>
                <li>Multi toolhead for support/multi material</li>
                <li>High speed printing</li>
            </ul>


            <!-- Design Process -->
            <h2>Design & Development</h2>
            <p>
                Given the wide range of successful FFF printers, it would be foolish to start from scratch. My inpsiration 
                started with the Voron trident because of the effective core XY motion system, and 3 Z axes for 2 axis bed 
                tilt. I also was inspired by the E3D toolchanger and pantheon printers with their use of a large flat plate
                providing a consistent XY motion plane. While I don't want to develop my own toolchanger, I was inspired
                by the Prusa XL to leave a large space at the back for docking toolheads.
            </p>
            <h3>Key Design Points</h3>
            <p>
                1/5" T slot frame ensuring rigidity and providing an easy location for the high temperature rated insulation
                required to achieve the enclosure temperatures needed for true engineering materials.
            </p>
            <p>
                The XY motion system is built off a 1/2" MIC6 plate, serving as a robust and flat platform. The X axis
                gantry was planned to be a t slot extrusion, but it didn't inspire confidence in the rigidity as a platform
                so I switched to a stacked plate construction.
            </p>
            <p>
                triple Z axis motion system with ball screws acting as a platform for 2 axis bed tilt and built for constant
                bed motion.
            </p>
            <p>
                400mm MIC6 bed + fiberglass build plate to ensure flatness, minimizing warping when heated, and prevent build
                plate peeling seen on large parts printed on magnetic build plates.
            </p>

